{"title_page": "Ouarzazate Solar Power Station", "text_new": "{{update|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox power station\n| name = Ouarzazate Solar Power Station\n| name_official =\n| location = [[Ouarzazate]]\n| status = O\n| construction_began = May 2013\n| commissioned = February 2016<ref>{{cite news|title=Morocco commissions first phase of Noor-Ouarzazate solar power project|url=http://www.power-technology.com/news/newsmorocco-commissions-first-phase-noor-ouarzazate-solar-power-project-4803152|accessdate=6 February 2016|publisher=power-technology.com|date=5 February 2016}}{{Unreliable source?|reason=domain on WP:BLACKLIST|date=June 2016}}</ref>\n| decommissioned =\n| cost = $2.5 Billion\n| operator =\n| solar_type = CSP\n| solar_csp_technology= Parabolic-through, Solar power tower\n| solar_csp_collectors= \n| solar_cpvt =\n| ps_units_manu_model =\n| ps_site_area = {{convert|2500|ha|acre|0}}\n| solar_site_resource = 2635 kWh/m<sup>2</sup>/yr\n| ps_electrical_capacity= 160 [[Megawatt|MW]] (Noor I)<br/>200 [[Megawatt|MW]] (Noor II)<br/>150 [[Megawatt|MW]] (Noor III)<ref>{{cite news| url=http://helioscsp.com/chinese-firm-helps-build-worlds-largest-concentrated-solar-power-complex-in-moroccos-desert/ | title=Chinese firm helps build world\u2019s largest concentrated solar power complex in Morocco\u2019s desert|access-date=22 January 2019}}</ref><br/>510 [[Megawatt|MW]] (total)\n| ps_cooling_source=El Mansour Eddahbi Dam/Reservoir\n| ps_electrical_cap_fac=\n| ps_annual_generation= 370 [[GWh]] (Noor I)<br/>600 [[GWh]] (Noor II)<br/>500 [[GWh]] (Noor III)\n| website =\n| extra =\n}}\n\n'''Ouarzazate Solar Power Station''' (OSPS), also called '''Noor Power Station''' (\u0646\u0648\u0631, [[Arabic]] for [[light]]) is a solar power complex located in the [[Dr\u00e2a-Tafilalet]] region in [[Morocco]], {{convert|10|km}} from [[Ouarzazate]] town, in Ghessat rural council area. At 510 MW, it is the world's largest [[concentrated solar power]] plant. With an additional 72 MW [[photovoltaic system]] the entire project is planned to produce 582&nbsp;MW at peak when finished and is being built in three phases and in four parts. The total project's estimated cost is around $2.5 billion.<ref> https://ledesk.ma/2017/04/01/noor-iv-lance-parachevant-la-mega-centrale-solaire-de-ouarzazate/ </ref>\n\nThe plant will be able to store solar energy in the form of heated [[molten salt]], allowing for production of electricity into the night. \nPhase 1 comes with a full-load molten salt storage capacity of 3 hours. \nNoor II, commissioned in 2018,<ref name=noor2nrel /> and Noor III, commissioned in January 2019, store energy for up to eight hours.<ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite news | last1 = Neslen | first1 = Arthur | title = Morocco poised to become a solar superpower with launch of desert mega-project | url = https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2015/oct/26/morocco-poised-to-become-a-solar-superpower-with-launch-of-desert-mega-project | accessdate = 27 October 2015 | work = [[The Guardian]] | date = 26 October 2015}}</ref>\nIt will cover an area of {{convert|2500|ha|acre|0}}.{{citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n\nThe project is being developed with the help of the Spanish consortium [[TSK Group|TSK]]-[[Acciona]]-[[SENER|Sener]] and is the first in a series of planned developments at the Ouarzazate Solar Complex by the Moroccan Agency for Solar Energy ([[Moroccan Agency for Sustainable Energy|MASEN]]). As of December 2015, the plant was expected to begin commercial operation in June 2017.<ref>''[http://www.worldbank.org/projects/P122028/ma-ouarzazate-concentrated-solar-power?lang=en&tab=results Project > MA-Ouarzazate Concentrated Solar Power > Results]'', World Bank, accessed 2015-12-28</ref>\n\nWater consumption for the Ouarzazate Noor complex is estimated at 2.5 to 3 million m<sup>3</sup> per year for one wet- cooling project (Noor I) and two dry \u2013 cooling projects (Noor II and III), due to the need to clean the reflectors regularly.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.afdb.org/fileadmin/uploads/afdb/Documents/Environmental-and-Social-Assessments/Morocco_-_Ouarzazate_Solar_Power_Station_Project_II_-_ESIA_Summary.pdf|title = Ouarzazate Solar Power Complex, Phase 1<br/> Morocco <br/>Specific Environmental and Social Impact Assessment|date = |access-date = |website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n\n== Noor I ==\n[[File:Ouarzazate - Noor 1 inauguration - NASA.jpg|thumb|Noor 1 nearing inauguration in December 2015]]\n\nOuarzazate Solar Power Station (OSPS) &ndash; Phase 1, also referred to as '''Noor I CSP''', has an installed capacity of 160 [[Megawatt|MW]]. It was connected to the Moroccan power grid on 5 February 2016.<ref>{{Cite web | last= Vorrath | first= Sophie | title= First 160MW of huge Noor solar thermal plant connected to Moroccan grid | date= 2016-02-05 | website= RenewEconomy | url= http://reneweconomy.com.au/2016/first-160mw-of-huge-noor-solar-thermal-plant-connected-to-moroccan-grid-18132 | access-date= 2016-07-19}}</ref>\nIt covers {{convert|450|ha|acre|0}} and is expected to deliver 370 [[GWh]] per year.<ref>{{Cite web | last= | first= | title= Project Ourzazate Solar Power Station \u2013 Phase I <br/>Country: Kingdom of Morocco <br/>Project Appraisal Report<br/>Date: April 2012 | date= | website= | publisher= | url= http://www.afdb.org/fileadmin/uploads/afdb/Documents/Project-and-Operations/Morocco_-_AR_Ouarzazate_Project_I_.pdf | access-date=}}</ref>\nThe plant is a [[parabolic trough]] type with a molten salt storage for 3 hours of low-light producing capacity.\n\nThe cost of the project when it began operations was $3.9 billion.<ref name=\"Neslen\">{{Cite news | first = Arthur | last = Neslen | title = Morocco to switch on first phase of world's largest solar plant | newspaper = The Guardian | date = 2016-02-04 | issn = 0261-3077 | url = https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2016/feb/04/morocco-to-switch-on-first-phase-of-worlds-largest-solar-plant | access-date = 2016-02-07 | language = en-GB}}</ref> It uses half a million mirrors.<ref>{{Cite web | title= Morocco's Massive Desert Solar Project Starts Up | website= MIT Technology Review | url= https://www.technologyreview.com/s/600751/moroccos-massive-desert-solar-project-starts-up/#/set/id/600752/ | access-date= 2016-02-09}}</ref>\n\nThe design uses wet cooling and the need to regularly clean the reflectors means that the water use is high &ndash; 1.7 million m<sup>3</sup> per year or 4.6 liters per [[Kilowatt hour|kWh]].<ref>{{Cite web | last= | first= | title= Ouarzazate Solar Power Complex, Phase 1<br/> Morocco <br/>Specific Environmental and Social Impact Assessment<br/>Volume 1 | date= | website= | publisher= | url= http://www.masen.org.ma/upload/environnement/OZZ1_SESIA_Volume_1_%28SESIA%29.pdf | access-date=}}</ref>\nWater usage is more than double the water usage of a wet cooled coal power station and 23 times the water use per kWh of a dry cooled coal power station,<ref>{{Cite web | title= Majuba Power Station | website= www.eskom.co.za | url= http://www.eskom.co.za/Whatweredoing/ElectricityGeneration/PowerStations/Pages/Majuba_Power_Station.aspx | access-date= 2016-02-08}}</ref> though life-cycle [[greenhouse gas]] emissions of solar thermal plants show that generating comparable energy from coal typically releases around 20 times more carbon dioxide than renewable sources.<ref>{{Cite web | title= NREL: Energy Analysis - Life Cycle Assessment Harmonization Results and Findings | website= www.nrel.gov | url= http://www.nrel.gov/analysis/sustain_lca_results.html | access-date= 2016-11-01 | url-status= dead | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20170506114117/http://www.nrel.gov/analysis/sustain_lca_results.html | archivedate= 2017-05-06 }}</ref>\n\nThe electricity was to be sold at $0.19 /kWh.<ref>{{Cite web | title= Morocco starts production at 160 MW solar plant - Agricultural Commodities -Reuters | website= af.reuters.com | url= https://af.reuters.com/article/commoditiesNews/idAFL8N15J4PR | access-date= 2016-02-08}}</ref>\n\nThe monthly production of electricity of the power plant Noor I in 2017 in MWh was:<ref>\u00ab https://noorouarzazate.blogspot.com/ \u00bb, ''[[These data were given by a student that made his internship in Nomac]]'', April 23th,  2019.</ref><ref>\u00ab https://www.nomac.com/en/our-operations/nomac-globally/nooro-i-csp-ipp/ \u00bb, ''[[Nomac]]'', January 2019.</ref> \nJanuary: 30261.44 ;\t\nFebruary: 19418.25 ;\t\nMarch: 48605.63 ;\t\nApril: 40376.02 ;\t\nMay: 45445.62 ;\nJune: 33369.19 ;\t\nJuly: 42276.52 ;\t\nAugust: 30850 ;\t\nSeptember: 41205.18 ;\t\nOctober: 31973.98 ;\t\nNovember: 22689.4 ;\nDecember: 27628.56.\n\n== Noor II ==\n\n'''Noor II CSP''' is the second phase of the Ouarzazate Solar Power Station. \nIt is a 200 [[Megawatt|MW]] CSP solar plant using parabolic troughs. \nIt has a 7 hours storage capacity.<ref name=nrel />\nIt covers an area of {{convert|680|ha|acre|0}} and is expected to supply 600 GWh per year.<ref name=AFDB-01>{{Cite web | last = | first = | title = Ouarzazate Solar Complex Project \u2013 Phase II (NOORo II AND NOORo III power plants) | date = | website = | publisher = | url = http://www.afdb.org/fileadmin/uploads/afdb/Documents/Project-and-Operations/MOROCCO-AR_-_Ouarzazate_Solar_Complex_Project-_Phase_II_-_12_2014.pdf | access-date =}}</ref>\nConstruction started in February 2016<ref name=nrel>{{cite web|title=Concentrating Solar Power Projects - NOOR II {{!}} Concentrating Solar Power {{!}} NREL|url=http://www.nrel.gov/csp/solarpaces/project_detail.cfm/projectID=4292|website=www.nrel.gov|accessdate=1 December 2016}}</ref> and the plant was commissioned in January 2018.<ref name=\"noor2nrel\">{{cite web|title=Concentrating Solar Power Projects - NOOR II {{!}} Concentrating Solar Power {{!}} NREL|url=https://www.nrel.gov/csp/solarpaces/project_detail.cfm/projectID=4292|website=www.nrel.gov|accessdate=26 February 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIt uses a dry cooling system to decrease water use.<ref name=AFDB-02>{{Cite web | last = | first = | title = Project: Ouarzazate Solar Power Station Project II<br/>Country: Morocco<br/>Summary environmental and social impact assessment | date = | publisher = | website = | url = http://www.afdb.org/fileadmin/uploads/afdb/Documents/Environmental-and-Social-Assessments/Morocco_-_Ouarzazate_Solar_Power_Station_Project_II_-_ESIA_Summary.pdf | access-date =\n}}</ref>\n\n== Noor III ==\n[[File:Ouarzazate Power Station Noor III Solar Tower.jpg|thumb|Noor III solar tower at dusk]]\n\n'''Noor III CSP''' is the third part of the Ouarzazate Solar Power Station. It is a 150 MW gross CSP solar project using a [[solar power tower]] with 7 hours energy storage.<ref name=\"nrel_noor3\">{{cite web | url= https://solarpaces.nrel.gov/noor-iii | title=Concentrating Solar Power Projects - NOOR III | website= solarpaces.nrel.gov | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20181212062951/https://solarpaces.nrel.gov/noor-iii | archivedate= 12 December 2018 | url-status= live | access-date= 12 December 2018 }}</ref> \nIt covers an area of {{convert|550|ha|acre|0}} and it is expected to supply 500 GW\u00b7h per year.<ref name=AFDB-01/>\nIt uses a dry cooling system to decrease water use.<ref name=AFDB-02/>\nThe CSP tower mirror field was commissioned in March 2018.<ref>{{Cite web | url= https://www.eurekalert.org/pub_releases/2018-03/s-w2u030918.php | title= World's second utility-scale 24/7 tower CSP, Noor III commissions solar field | date= 11 March 2018 | website= www.eurekalert.org | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180312200709/https://www.eurekalert.org/pub_releases/2018-03/s-w2u030918.php | archivedate= 12 March 2018 | url-status= live | access-date= 12 December 2018 }}</ref> \nNoor III is the fifth ever built utility-scale CSP tower, but the second with energy storage, after the 125 MW gross [[Crescent Dunes Solar Energy Project|Crescent Dunes]]. At 150 MW Noor III is now the most powerful CSP tower unit built.<ref>{{Cite web | url= https://www.modernpowersystems.com/features/featurefirst-synchronisation-of-phase-iii-of-the-worlds-largest-csp-6822494/ | title= First synchronisation of phase III of the world\u2019s largest CSP | date= 28 October 2018 | website= www.modernpowersystems.com | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20181212065836/https://www.modernpowersystems.com/features/featurefirst-synchronisation-of-phase-iii-of-the-worlds-largest-csp-6822494/ | archivedate= 12 December 2018 | url-status= live | access-date= 12 December 2018 }}</ref> \nIn September 2018 the CSP tower unit was first time synchronized to the power grid. In December Noor III completed a 10-day reliability test demonstrating that the project can provide continuous rated power even in the absence of sunlight.<ref>{{Cite web | url= https://www.powermag.com/moroccan-molten-salt-tower-project-clears-reliability-test/ | title= Moroccan Molten Salt Tower Project Clears Reliability Test | date= 2 December 2018 | website= www.powermag.com | access-date= 12 December 2018 }}</ref> The model HE54 heliostat has 54 mirrors with a total reflective surface of {{convert|178.5|sqm|sqft}}. \nThe solar field has 7400 of such mirrors. The tower is {{convert|250|m|ft}} high.\n\n== Noor IV ==\n\nNoor IV will be a 72 MW<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ledesk.ma/2017/04/01/noor-iv-lance-parachevant-la-mega-centrale-solaire-de-ouarzazate/|title=Noor IV lanc\u00e9e, parachevant la m\u00e9ga-centrale solaire de Ouarzazate|date=2017-04-01|website=Le Desk|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-24}}</ref> [[photovoltaic power station]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://renewablesnow.com/news/morocco-to-complete-noor-ouarzazate-solar-complex-by-mid-2018-602259|title=Morocco to complete Noor Ouarzazate solar complex by mid-2018|work=Renewablesnow.com|access-date=2018-11-22|language=en}}</ref> The total investment in this project is 750 million MAD.\n\n== See also ==\n{{commons category}}\n{{stack|{{Portal|Morocco|Renewable energy}}}}\n* [[List of solar thermal power stations]]\n* [[Solar thermal energy]]\n\n== References ==\n\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:Solar power stations in Morocco]]\n[[Category:Energy infrastructure completed in 2016]]\n[[Category:2016 establishments in Morocco]]\n[[Category:Solar thermal energy]]\n", "text_old": "{{update|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox power station\n| name = Ouarzazate Solar Power Station\n| name_official =\n| location = [[Ouarzazate]]\n| status = O\n| construction_began = May 2013\n| commissioned = February 2016<ref>{{cite news|title=Morocco commissions first phase of Noor-Ouarzazate solar power project|url=http://www.power-technology.com/news/newsmorocco-commissions-first-phase-noor-ouarzazate-solar-power-project-4803152|accessdate=6 February 2016|publisher=power-technology.com|date=5 February 2016}}{{Unreliable source?|reason=domain on WP:BLACKLIST|date=June 2016}}</ref>\n| decommissioned =\n| cost = $2.5 Billion\n| operator =\n| solar_type = CSP\n| solar_csp_technology= Parabolic-through, Solar power tower\n| solar_csp_collectors= \n| solar_cpvt =\n| ps_units_manu_model =\n| ps_site_area = {{convert|2500|ha|acre|0}}\n| solar_site_resource = 2635 kWh/m<sup>2</sup>/yr\n| ps_electrical_capacity= 160 [[Megawatt|MW]] (Noor I)<br/>200 [[Megawatt|MW]] (Noor II)<br/>150 [[Megawatt|MW]] (Noor III)<ref>{{cite news| url=http://helioscsp.com/chinese-firm-helps-build-worlds-largest-concentrated-solar-power-complex-in-moroccos-desert/ | title=Chinese firm helps build world\u2019s largest concentrated solar power complex in Morocco\u2019s desert|access-date=22 January 2019}}</ref><br/>510 [[Megawatt|MW]] (total)\n| ps_cooling_source=El Mansour Eddahbi Dam/Reservoir\n| ps_electrical_cap_fac=\n| ps_annual_generation= 370 [[GWh]] (Noor I)<br/>600 [[GWh]] (Noor II)<br/>500 [[GWh]] (Noor III)\n| website =\n| extra =\n}}\n\n'''Ouarzazate Solar Power Station''' (OSPS), also called '''Noor Power Station''' (\u0646\u0648\u0631, [[Arabic]] for [[light]]) is a solar power complex located in the [[Dr\u00e2a-Tafilalet]] region in [[Morocco]], {{convert|10|km}} from [[Ouarzazate]] town, in Ghessat rural council area. At 510 MW, it is the world's largest [[concentrated solar power]] plant. With an additional 72 MW [[photovoltaic system]] the entire project is planned to produce 582&nbsp;MW at peak when finished and is being built in three phases and in four parts. The total project's estimated cost is around $2.5 billion.<ref> https://ledesk.ma/2017/04/01/noor-iv-lance-parachevant-la-mega-centrale-solaire-de-ouarzazate/ </ref>\n\nThe plant will be able to store solar energy in the form of heated [[molten salt]], allowing for production of electricity into the night. \nPhase 1 comes with a full-load molten salt storage capacity of 3 hours. \nNoor II, commissioned in 2018,<ref name=noor2nrel /> and Noor III, commissioned in January 2019, store energy for up to eight hours.<ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite news | last1 = Neslen | first1 = Arthur | title = Morocco poised to become a solar superpower with launch of desert mega-project | url = https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2015/oct/26/morocco-poised-to-become-a-solar-superpower-with-launch-of-desert-mega-project | accessdate = 27 October 2015 | work = [[The Guardian]] | date = 26 October 2015}}</ref>\nIt will cover an area of {{convert|2500|ha|acre|0}}.{{citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n\nThe project is being developed with the help of the Spanish consortium [[TSK Group|TSK]]-[[Acciona]]-[[SENER|Sener]] and is the first in a series of planned developments at the Ouarzazate Solar Complex by the Moroccan Agency for Solar Energy ([[Moroccan Agency for Sustainable Energy|MASEN]]). As of December 2015, the plant was expected to begin commercial operation in June 2017.<ref>''[http://www.worldbank.org/projects/P122028/ma-ouarzazate-concentrated-solar-power?lang=en&tab=results Project > MA-Ouarzazate Concentrated Solar Power > Results]'', World Bank, accessed 2015-12-28</ref>\n\nWater consumption for the Ouarzazate Noor complex is estimated at 2.5 to 3 million m<sup>3</sup> per year for one wet- cooling project (Noor I) and two dry \u2013 cooling projects (Noor II and III), due to the need to clean the reflectors regularly.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.afdb.org/fileadmin/uploads/afdb/Documents/Environmental-and-Social-Assessments/Morocco_-_Ouarzazate_Solar_Power_Station_Project_II_-_ESIA_Summary.pdf|title = Ouarzazate Solar Power Complex, Phase 1<br/> Morocco <br/>Specific Environmental and Social Impact Assessment|date = |access-date = |website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n\n== Noor I ==\n[[File:Ouarzazate - Noor 1 inauguration - NASA.jpg|thumb|Noor 1 nearing inauguration in December 2015]]\n\nOuarzazate Solar Power Station (OSPS) &ndash; Phase 1, also referred to as '''Noor I CSP''', has an installed capacity of 160 [[Megawatt|MW]]. It was connected to the Moroccan power grid on 5 February 2016.<ref>{{Cite web | last= Vorrath | first= Sophie | title= First 160MW of huge Noor solar thermal plant connected to Moroccan grid | date= 2016-02-05 | website= RenewEconomy | url= http://reneweconomy.com.au/2016/first-160mw-of-huge-noor-solar-thermal-plant-connected-to-moroccan-grid-18132 | access-date= 2016-07-19}}</ref>\nIt covers {{convert|450|ha|acre|0}} and is expected to deliver 370 [[GWh]] per year.<ref>{{Cite web | last= | first= | title= Project Ourzazate Solar Power Station \u2013 Phase I <br/>Country: Kingdom of Morocco <br/>Project Appraisal Report<br/>Date: April 2012 | date= | website= | publisher= | url= http://www.afdb.org/fileadmin/uploads/afdb/Documents/Project-and-Operations/Morocco_-_AR_Ouarzazate_Project_I_.pdf | access-date=}}</ref>\nThe plant is a [[parabolic trough]] type with a molten salt storage for 3 hours of low-light producing capacity.\n\nThe cost of the project when it began operations was $3.9 billion.<ref name=\"Neslen\">{{Cite news | first = Arthur | last = Neslen | title = Morocco to switch on first phase of world's largest solar plant | newspaper = The Guardian | date = 2016-02-04 | issn = 0261-3077 | url = https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2016/feb/04/morocco-to-switch-on-first-phase-of-worlds-largest-solar-plant | access-date = 2016-02-07 | language = en-GB}}</ref> It uses half a million mirrors.<ref>{{Cite web | title= Morocco's Massive Desert Solar Project Starts Up | website= MIT Technology Review | url= https://www.technologyreview.com/s/600751/moroccos-massive-desert-solar-project-starts-up/#/set/id/600752/ | access-date= 2016-02-09}}</ref>\n\nThe design uses wet cooling and the need to regularly clean the reflectors means that the water use is high &ndash; 1.7 million m<sup>3</sup> per year or 4.6 liters per [[Kilowatt hour|kWh]].<ref>{{Cite web | last= | first= | title= Ouarzazate Solar Power Complex, Phase 1<br/> Morocco <br/>Specific Environmental and Social Impact Assessment<br/>Volume 1 | date= | website= | publisher= | url= http://www.masen.org.ma/upload/environnement/OZZ1_SESIA_Volume_1_%28SESIA%29.pdf | access-date=}}</ref>\nWater usage is more than double the water usage of a wet cooled coal power station and 23 times the water use per kWh of a dry cooled coal power station,<ref>{{Cite web | title= Majuba Power Station | website= www.eskom.co.za | url= http://www.eskom.co.za/Whatweredoing/ElectricityGeneration/PowerStations/Pages/Majuba_Power_Station.aspx | access-date= 2016-02-08}}</ref> though life-cycle [[greenhouse gas]] emissions of solar thermal plants show that generating comparable energy from coal typically releases around 20 times more carbon dioxide than renewable sources.<ref>{{Cite web | title= NREL: Energy Analysis - Life Cycle Assessment Harmonization Results and Findings | website= www.nrel.gov | url= http://www.nrel.gov/analysis/sustain_lca_results.html | access-date= 2016-11-01 | url-status= dead | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20170506114117/http://www.nrel.gov/analysis/sustain_lca_results.html | archivedate= 2017-05-06 }}</ref>\n\nThe electricity was to be sold at $0.19 /kWh.<ref>{{Cite web | title= Morocco starts production at 160 MW solar plant - Agricultural Commodities -Reuters | website= af.reuters.com | url= https://af.reuters.com/article/commoditiesNews/idAFL8N15J4PR | access-date= 2016-02-08}}</ref>\n\nThe monthly production of electricity of the power plant Noor I in 2017 in MWh was:<ref>\u00ab https://noorouarzazate.blogspot.com/ \u00bb, ''[[These data were given by a student that made his internship in Nomac]]'', April 23th,  2019.</ref><ref>\u00ab https://www.nomac.com/en/our-operations/nomac-globally/nooro-i-csp-ipp/ \u00bb, ''[[Nomac]]'', January 2019.</ref> \nJanuary: 30261.44 ;\t\nFebruary: 19418.25 ;\t\nMarch: 48605.63 ;\t\nApril: 40376.02 ;\t\nMay: 45445.62 ;\nJune: 33369.19 ;\t\nJuly: 42276.52 ;\t\nAugust: 30850 ;\t\nSeptember: 41205.18 ;\t\nOctober: 31973.98 ;\t\nNovember: 22689.4 ;\nDecember: 27628.56.\n\n== Noor II ==\n\n'''Noor II CSP''' is the second phase of the Ouarzazate Solar Power Station. \nIt is a 200 [[Megawatt|MW]] CSP solar plant using parabolic troughs. \nIt has a 7 hours storage capacity.<ref name=nrel />\nIt covers an area of {{convert|680|ha|acre|0}} and is expected to supply 600 GWh per year.<ref name=AFDB-01>{{Cite web | last = | first = | title = Ouarzazate Solar Complex Project \u2013 Phase II (NOORo II AND NOORo III power plants) | date = | website = | publisher = | url = http://www.afdb.org/fileadmin/uploads/afdb/Documents/Project-and-Operations/MOROCCO-AR_-_Ouarzazate_Solar_Complex_Project-_Phase_II_-_12_2014.pdf | access-date =}}</ref>\nConstruction started in February 2016<ref name=nrel>{{cite web|title=Concentrating Solar Power Projects - NOOR II {{!}} Concentrating Solar Power {{!}} NREL|url=http://www.nrel.gov/csp/solarpaces/project_detail.cfm/projectID=4292|website=www.nrel.gov|accessdate=1 December 2016}}</ref> and the plant was commissioned in January 2018.<ref name=\"noor2nrel\">{{cite web|title=Concentrating Solar Power Projects - NOOR II {{!}} Concentrating Solar Power {{!}} NREL|url=https://www.nrel.gov/csp/solarpaces/project_detail.cfm/projectID=4292|website=www.nrel.gov|accessdate=26 February 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIt uses a dry cooling system to decrease water use.<ref name=AFDB-02>{{Cite web | last = | first = | title = Project: Ouarzazate Solar Power Station Project II<br/>Country: Morocco<br/>Summary environmental and social impact assessment | date = | publisher = | website = | url = http://www.afdb.org/fileadmin/uploads/afdb/Documents/Environmental-and-Social-Assessments/Morocco_-_Ouarzazate_Solar_Power_Station_Project_II_-_ESIA_Summary.pdf | access-date =\n}}</ref>\n\n== Noor III ==\n[[File:Ouarzazate Power Station Noor III Solar Tower.jpg|thumb|Noor III solar tower at dusk]]\n\n'''Noor III CSP''' is the third part of the Ouarzazate Solar Power Station. It is a 150 MW gross CSP solar project using a [[solar power tower]] with 7 hours energy storage.<ref name=\"nrel_noor3\">{{cite web | url= https://solarpaces.nrel.gov/noor-iii | title=Concentrating Solar Power Projects - NOOR III | website= solarpaces.nrel.gov | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20181212062951/https://solarpaces.nrel.gov/noor-iii | archivedate= 12 December 2018 | url-status= live | access-date= 12 December 2018 }}</ref> \nIt covers an area of {{convert|550|ha|acre|0}} and it is expected to supply 500 GW\u00b7h per year.<ref name=AFDB-01/>\nIt uses a dry cooling system to decrease water use.<ref name=AFDB-02/>\nThe CSP tower mirror field was commissioned in March 2018.<ref>{{Cite web | url= https://www.eurekalert.org/pub_releases/2018-03/s-w2u030918.php | title= World's second utility-scale 24/7 tower CSP, Noor III commissions solar field | date= 11 March 2018 | website= www.eurekalert.org | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180312200709/https://www.eurekalert.org/pub_releases/2018-03/s-w2u030918.php | archivedate= 12 March 2018 | url-status= live | access-date= 12 December 2018 }}</ref> \nNoor III is the fifth ever built utility-scale CSP tower, but the second with energy storage, after the 125 MW gross [[Crescent Dunes Solar Energy Project|Crescent Dunes]]. At 150 MW Noor III is now the most powerful CSP tower unit built.<ref>{{Cite web | url= https://www.modernpowersystems.com/features/featurefirst-synchronisation-of-phase-iii-of-the-worlds-largest-csp-6822494/ | title= First synchronisation of phase III of the world\u2019s largest CSP | date= 28 October 2018 | website= www.modernpowersystems.com | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20181212065836/https://www.modernpowersystems.com/features/featurefirst-synchronisation-of-phase-iii-of-the-worlds-largest-csp-6822494/ | archivedate= 12 December 2018 | url-status= live | access-date= 12 December 2018 }}</ref> \nIn September 2018 the CSP tower unit was first time synchronized to the power grid. In December Noor III completed a 10-day reliability test demonstrating that the project can provide continuous rated power even in the absence of sunlight.<ref>{{Cite web | url= https://www.powermag.com/moroccan-molten-salt-tower-project-clears-reliability-test/ | title= Moroccan Molten Salt Tower Project Clears Reliability Test | date= 2 December 2018 | website= www.powermag.com | access-date= 12 December 2018 }}</ref> The model HE54 heliostat has 54 mirrors with a total reflective surface of {{convert|178.5|sqm|sqft}}. \nThe solar field has 7400 of such mirrors. The tower is {{convert|250|m|ft}} high.\n\n== Noor IV ==\n\nNoor IV will be a 72 MW<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ledesk.ma/2017/04/01/noor-iv-lance-parachevant-la-mega-centrale-solaire-de-ouarzazate/|title=Noor IV lanc\u00e9e, parachevant la m\u00e9ga-centrale solaire de Ouarzazate|date=2017-04-01|website=Le Desk|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-24}}</ref> [[Photovoltaic power station]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://renewablesnow.com/news/morocco-to-complete-noor-ouarzazate-solar-complex-by-mid-2018-602259|title=Morocco to complete Noor Ouarzazate solar complex by mid-2018|work=Renewablesnow.com|access-date=2018-11-22|language=en}}</ref> The total investment in this project is 750 million MAD.\n\n== See also ==\n{{commons category}}\n{{stack|{{Portal|Morocco|Renewable energy}}}}\n* [[List of solar thermal power stations]]\n* [[Solar thermal energy]]\n\n== References ==\n\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:Solar power stations in Morocco]]\n[[Category:Energy infrastructure completed in 2016]]\n[[Category:2016 establishments in Morocco]]\n[[Category:Solar thermal energy]]\n", "name_user": "Edcolins", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNoor IV:capitalization", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ouarzazate_Solar_Power_Station"}
{"title_page": "Glendale, Arizona", "text_new": "{{short description|City in Arizona, United States}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = Glendale\n|settlement_type          = [[City]]\n|image_skyline            = Glendale-Downtown Glendale.jpg\n|imagesize                = 260px\n|image_caption            = Downtown Glendale, Arizona as viewed from the intersections of Glendale Ave. and 58th Ave.\n|image_seal               = glendalelogo.jpg\n|image_map                = File:Maricopa County Arizona Incorporated and Unincorporated areas Glendale Highlighted 0427820.svg\n|mapsize                  = \n|map_caption              = Location of Glendale in Maricopa County, Arizona\n|image_map1               = \n|mapsize1                 = \n|map_caption1             = \n|pushpin_map              = USA\n|pushpin_map_caption      = Location in the United States\n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in Arizona|County]]\n|subdivision_name         = [[United States]]\n|subdivision_name1        = [[Arizona]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Maricopa County, Arizona|Maricopa]]\n|population_demonym       = Glendalian\n|government_type          = \n|leader_title             = [[Mayor]]\n|leader_name              = Jerry Weiers (Non-Partisan)\n|established_date         = \n|area_magnitude           = \n|area_total_km2           = 160.49\n|area_total_sq_mi         = 61.96\n|area_land_km2            = 159.45\n|area_land_sq_mi          = 61.56\n|area_water_km2           = 1.04\n|area_water_sq_mi         = 0.40\n|elevation_footnotes      = <ref name=gnis>{{Cite GNIS|5060|Glendale}}</ref>\n|elevation_ft             = 1152\n|elevation_m              = \n|population_as_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_est           = 250702\n|pop_est_as_of            = 2018\n|pop_est_footnotes        = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\"/>\n|population_footnotes     = <ref name =\"FactFinder\">{{cite web|title=American FactFinder|url=http://factfinder2.census.gov/faces/nav/jsf/pages/index.xhtml|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=June 18, 2012}}</ref>\n|population_total         = 226721\n|population_rank          = US: [[List of United States cities by population|89th]]\n|population_metro         = \n|population_density_km2   = 1572.28\n|population_density_sq_mi = 4072.15\n|timezone                 = [[Mountain Time Zone|MST]] (no [[Daylight savings time|DST]])\n|utc_offset               = -7\n|coordinates              = {{coord|33|32|19|N|112|11|11|W|region:US-AZ_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code_type         = ZIP code\n|postal_code              = 85301-85318\n|area_code                = [[Area code 623|623]] and [[Area code 602|602]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 04-27820\n|blank1_name              = GNIS_id = 5060<ref name=gnis/>\n|blank1_info              = \n|website                  = {{URL|www.glendaleaz.com}}\n|footnotes                = \n|unit_pref = Imperial\n|area_footnotes = <ref name=\"CenPopGazetteer2016\">{{cite web|title=2018 U.S. Gazetteer Files|url=https://www2.census.gov/geo/docs/maps-data/data/gazetteer/2018_Gazetteer/2018_gaz_place_04.txt|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=Jul 1, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Glendale''' {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u0261|l|\u025b|n|d|e\u026a|l}} is a city in [[Maricopa County, Arizona|Maricopa County]], [[Arizona]], [[United States]], located about nine miles (14&nbsp;km) northwest from [[Downtown Phoenix]]. According to the 2018 U.S. Census estimates, the population of the city is 250,702.<ref name =\"USCensusEst2018\"/>\n\n==History==\n{{Main|William John Murphy}}\nIn the late 1800s what is now known as Glendale, Arizona, was all desert. [[William John Murphy]], a native of [[New Hartford, New York]], who resided in the town of [[Flagstaff, Arizona|Flagstaff]] in what was then known as the territory of Arizona, was in charge of building a {{convert|40|mi|km|adj=mid|-long}} [[Arizona Canal]] from Granite Reef to New River for the Arizona Canal Company. In 1885, he completed the canal, which would bring water to the desert land.<ref name=\"M\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hmdb.org/marker.asp?marker=30433|title=William J. Murphy Historical Marker|website=www.hmdb.org}}</ref> Murphy was deep in debt, since he had agreed to be paid in Arizona Canal Company stock and bonds and land instead of cash.<ref name=\"SLRP\">{{cite web|url=http://www.waterhistory.org/histories/reclamation/saltriver/|title=WaterHistory.org|website=www.waterhistory.org}}</ref>\n[[File:William John Murphy.jpg|thumb|left|upright|William John Murphy \u2013 Founder of Glendale]]\nIn 1887, Murphy formed the Arizona Improvement Company. His objective was to sell the land and water rights south of the canal. Murphy had to raise capital from out of state sources in order to meet payroll and construction expenses.<ref name=\"SLRP\"/> Murphy decided to refer to this land as \"Glendale\". In order to develop and interest potential investors and settlers in this new town, Murphy decided to provide a better way of access from [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]] to Glendale and ending in the town of [[Peoria, Arizona|Peoria]] by building an {{convert|18|mi|km|adj=mid|-long}} diagonal road which he named Grand Avenue.\n\nIn 1891, Burgess Hadsell worked with Murphy to bring 70 Brethren and River Brethren families to Glendale to form a temperance colony. Soon settlers, attracted by the town's ban on alcoholic beverages, continued to arrive. In 1895, Murphy platted the original town site and amended the plat to include a town park and some business lots.  It was bounded by Lamar Road on the south, 55th Avenue on the east, Myrtle Avenue on the north, and 59th Avenue on the west.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.glendaleaz.com/economicdevelopment/documents/CCMP.pdf|title=Glendale City Center Master Plan|publisher=glendaleaz.com}}</ref> The construction of a railroad from Prescott to Phoenix was made possible with an exchange of the right-of-way made by Murphy along Grand Avenue.<ref name=\"M\"/>  The railroad allowed Glendale settlers to transport goods to the north and easily receive building materials.\n\nThe construction and commercial applications of the Beet Sugar Factory in 1906, also contributed to the growth of Glendale. Though the operations of the factory only lasted until 1913, it played an important role in the increase of immigrant and migrant settlers in the city.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://molokane.org/molokan/Locations/Americas/Arizona/Noon.htm|title=Beet Sugar Factory History, Glendale, Arizona|website=molokane.org}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nGlendale is located at {{Coord|33|32|19|N|112|11|11|W|type:city}} (33.538654, \u2212112.186261).<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/gazette.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=April 23, 2011|date=February 12, 2011|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref>\n\n===Climate===\n{{Phoenix weatherbox}}\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of {{convert|55.8|sqmi|km2}}, of which, {{convert|55.7|sqmi|km2}} of it is land and {{convert|0.1|sqmi|km2}} of it (0.13%) is water.\nHOT\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1910= 1000\n|1920= 2737\n|1930= 3665\n|1940= 4855\n|1950= 8179\n|1960= 15893\n|1970= 36228\n|1980= 97172\n|1990= 147864\n|2000= 218812\n|2010= 226721\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=250702\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=June 4, 2019}}</ref>\n|align-fn=center\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref name=\"DecennialCensus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 4, 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n\nAs of the [[census]] of 2010, there were 226,710 people, 79,114 households, and 54,721 families residing in the city. The [[population density]] was 3,929.5 people per square mile (1,517.3/km\u00b2). There were 79,667 housing units at an average density of 1,430.7 per square mile (552.4/km\u00b2). The racial makeup of the city was 75.54% [[Race (United States Census)|White]], 6% [[Race (United States Census)|Black]] or [[Race (United States Census)|African American]], 1.7% [[Race (United States Census)|Native American]], 3.9% [[Race (United States Census)|Asian]], 0.2% [[Race (United States Census)|Pacific Islander]], 16.95% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 4.0% from two or more races. 35.5% of the population were [[Race (United States Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Race (United States Census)|Latino]] of any race.\n\nThere were 79,114 households out of which 39.9% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 53.5% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 12.8% had a female householder with no husband present, and 28.2% were non-families. 21.3% of all households were made up of individuals and 5.8% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.85 and the average family size was 3.33.\n\nIn the city, the population was spread out with 30.1% under the age of 18, 10.8% from 18 to 24, 31.9% from 25 to 44, 19.9% from 45 to 64, and 7.4% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 31 years. For every 100 females, there were 99.6 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 97.1 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the city was $45,015, and the median income for a family was $51,162. Males had a median income of $35,901 versus $27,736 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the city was $19,124. About 8.8% of families and 11.9% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 15.3% of those under age 18 and 9.5% of those age 65 or over.\n{{clear}}\n\n==Notable attractions==\n[[File:Glendale Glitters by Gage Skidmore.jpg|thumb|Downtown Glendale with Glendale Glitters around Christmas]]\n[[File:WestgateAtNight.jpg|thumb|The fountain area of the Westgate Entertainment District.]]\n\n* [[Adobe Mountain Desert Park]]\n* Glendale Chocolate Festival (every February)<ref name=\"glendaleaz.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.glendaleaz.com/events/|title=Glendale, AZ - Events and Festivals|website=www.glendaleaz.com}}</ref>  \n* Glendale Folk & Heritage Festival<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.azcentral.com/thingstodo/events/articles/20130320glendale-folk-heritage-festival-event.html|title=3/23-24: Glendale Folk & Heritage Festival|first=Kellie|last=Hwang|website=azcentral.com}}</ref> \n* Glendale Glitters (every December)<ref name=\"glendaleaz.com\"/>\n* Glendale Jazz and Blues Festival<ref name=\"glendaleaz.com\"/>\n* Historic [[Manistee Ranch]]\n* Historic [[Sahuaro Ranch]]\n* Cerreta Candy Co. factory tour<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tripsavvy.com/cerreta-candy-company-factory-tour-2681124|title=The Sweetest Tour in Glendale, Arizona|website=TripSavvy}}</ref>\n* Downtown Glendale featuring antique shops and restaurants\n* [[Deer Valley Rock Art Center]]\n*[[State Farm Stadium]]\n*[[Gila River Arena]]\n*Brelby Theatre Company\n*Spotlight Youth Theatre\n* [[Elsie McCarthy Sensory Garden]]\n* Westgate Entertainment District\n\n==Sports==\n[[File:Westgateground.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Westgate City Center]][[File:Cardinals stadium crop.jpg|thumb|right|[[State Farm Stadium]]]]\n[[File:Glendale-arena.jpg|thumb|left|[[Gila River Arena]]]]\n[[File:University of Phoenix Stadium (Glendale).jpg|thumb|right|Ground level of the stadium.]]\n\nGlendale is the site of two major sports venues:  [[State Farm Stadium]] and [[Gila River Arena]]. Both venues are part of the Glendale Sports and Entertainment District development plan, meant to spur growth in the sparsely inhabited Yucca district. Both venues are owned by the City of Glendale.\n\nState Farm Stadium has been the home field of the [[Arizona Cardinals]] in the [[National Football League]] since 2006, and the annual [[Fiesta Bowl]] college football game since 2007. Both the Cardinals and bowl game moved from [[Sun Devil Stadium]] on the [[Arizona State University]] campus in [[Tempe, Arizona|Tempe]]. Since opening, the facility has brought two [[Super Bowl]]s, three college football national championship games, the [[NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|NCAA Men's Basketball Final Four]], [[WrestleMania XXVI]] and [[International Champions Cup]] soccer to Glendale. Designed by architect Peter Eisenman, the stadium was featured on [[History (U.S. TV channel)|The History Channel]] TV series, ''[[Modern Marvels]]'' because of its roll-out natural grass field.\n\n[[Gila River Arena]] (formerly Glendale Arena, then Jobing.com Arena) and [[Westgate City Center]] is adjacent to State Farm Stadium, and is the home of the [[Arizona Coyotes]] of the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL). It was also the home of the now defunct [[Arizona Sting]] of the [[National Lacrosse League]] (NLL). The inaugural [[Street League Skateboarding]] event was held in the summer of 2010 in Glendale at the Gila River Arena. This street skateboarding competition returns to Glendale annually.\n\nIn 2009, the [[Los Angeles Dodgers]] and the [[Chicago White Sox]]  of [[Major League Baseball]] began to share the new  [[Camelback Ranch|Camelback Ranch-Glendale]] spring training complex and stadium in Glendale owned and operated by the City of Glendale.\n\n==Education==\n[[File:Glendale-1917 Nash Fire Truck.jpg|thumb|right|This 1917 Nash Fire Truck was the first motorized fire truck of the Glendale Fire Department. The truck was manufactured by the [[Nash Motors|Nash Motors Company]] and is on exhibit at the Glendale Training Center located at 11330 W. Glendale Ave. in Glendale, Arizona.]]\nThere are a number of higher education campuses in Glendale. [[Glendale Community College (Arizona)|Glendale Community College]] and Glendale Community College North, just across the border in northwestern Phoenix, are members of the [[Maricopa County Community College District]]. [[Arizona State University's]] [[Thunderbird School of Global Management]] was founded in Glendale at Thunderbird Field after World War II and recently relocated its campus to the downtown location of ASU after joining the university as an independent unit dedicated to international business education. [[Arizona State University at the West campus|West]] campus is just across the border from Glendale in west Phoenix.  [[Midwestern University]] is a graduate college of medicine located in Glendale.\n\nMany [[school districts]] serve the city of Glendale.\n\nThe following school districts serve the city:\n*Unified school districts\n**[[Deer Valley Unified School District]]\n**[[Dysart Unified School District]]\n**[[Peoria Unified School District]] (headquartered in Glendale)<ref>\"[https://www.peoriaud.k12.az.us/Pages/DistrictOverview.aspx District Overview]\" {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120730183918/https://www.peoriaud.k12.az.us/Pages/DistrictOverview.aspx |date=July 30, 2012 }}</ref>\n*High school districts\n**[[Glendale Union High School District]]\n**[[Phoenix Union High School District]]\n**Tolleson Union High School District\n*Elementary school districts\n**[[Alhambra Elementary School District]]\n**Glendale Elementary School District\n**Pendergast Elementary School District\n**[[Washington Elementary School District]]\n\nGrace Lutheran School is a Pre-K-8 Christian school of the [[Wisconsin Evangelical Lutheran Synod]] (WELS) in Glendale.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.graceglendale.org/school/|title=School|website=Grace Evangelical Lutheran Church}}</ref>\n\n==Transportation==\nThe city of Glendale has a roughly average percentage of households without a car. In 2015, 8.4 percent of Glendale households lacked a car, and increased slightly to 9 percent in 2016. The national average was 8.7 percent in 2016. Glendale averaged 1.72 cars per household in 2016, compared to a national average of 1.8.<ref>{{cite web|title=Car Ownership in U.S. Cities Data and Map|journal=Governing|url=http://www.governing.com/gov-data/car-ownership-numbers-of-vehicles-by-city-map.html|accessdate=May 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Martha McSally and Jerry Weiers.jpg|thumb|Glendale Mayor Jerry Weiers with Martha McSally in 2020.]]\n==Notable people==\n<!-- NOTICE * * * NOTICE * * * NOTICE * * * * * * * * * * * *NOTICE * * * NOTICE * * * NOTICE\u2022 Only people who already have a Wikipedia article may appear here. This establishes notability.\n\u2022 The article must mention how they are associated with the community, whether born, raised, or residing.\n\u2022 The fact of their association should have a reliable source cited, or it should be stated in their Wikipedia article\n\u2022 Alphabetical by last name please\n\u2022 All others will be deleted without further explanation\nEND OF NOTICE * * * * * * * * * * * * END OF NOTICE * * * * * * * * * * * *END OF NOTICE -->\n*[[Prince Amukamara]] \u2013 professional football player\n*[[Eddie Bonine]] \u2013 professional baseball player\n*[[Elijah Burke]] \u2013 professional wrestler\n*[[Daniel Cruz (soccer)|Danny Cruz]] \u2013 professional soccer player\n*[[Nick Evans (baseball)|Nick Evans]] \u2013 professional baseball player\n*[[Trent Franks]] \u2013  former United States congressman\n*[[Lauren Froderman]] \u2013 winner of ''So You Think You Can Dance'' (Season 7)\n*[[Jennie Garth]] \u2013 actress\n*[[Benson Henderson]] \u2013 former UFC Lightweight Champion<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ufc.com/fighter/Benson-Henderson | publisher=UFC | title=Benson Henderson | accessdate=September 5, 2014 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140819071228/http://www.ufc.com/fighter/Benson-Henderson | archivedate=August 19, 2014}}</ref>\n*[[Job for a Cowboy]] \u2013 death metal band formed in Glendale in 2003\n*[[Paul LoDuca]] \u2013 professional baseball player\n*[[Craig Mabbitt]] \u2013 lead vocalist of band [[Escape The Fate]]\n*[[Michael McDowell (racing driver)|Michael McDowell]] \u2013 NASCAR driver\n*[[Evan Mecham]] \u2013 Arizona governor\n*[[Lou Novikoff]] \u2013 professional baseball player\n*[[Sterling Ridge]] \u2013 Arizona legislator\n*[[Marty Robbins]] \u2013 Grammy-winning country musician and auto racer\n*[[Nate Ruess]] \u2013 lead singer of [[Fun (band)|Fun]]\n*[[Tage Thompson]] - NHL player for the [[Buffalo Sabres]]\n*[[Jason Zumwalt]] \u2013 actor\n\n==Culture==\n===Arizona's Antique Capital===\nGlendale bills itself as \"Arizona's Antique Capital\", with support for its claim from both ''[[Sunset (magazine)|Sunset]]'' magazine ([https://web.archive.org/web/20081031092720/http://www.sunset.com/sunset/travel/article/0%2C20633%2C710517%2C00.html 2004]) and a 1998 article in ''[[USA Today]]''. Glendale is home to the popular [[Arrowhead Towne Center]] mall in the northwest part of the city. Glendale also is home to [[Midwestern University]], metropolitan Phoenix's first medical school, as well as a major post-graduate international business school: the [[Thunderbird School of Global Management]].\n\nAn extension of [[Valley Metro Rail]] service is planned to serve the city, opening in 2026,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.valleymetro.org/metro_light_rail/future_extensions/glendale/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110518122555/http://www.valleymetro.org/metro_light_rail/future_extensions/glendale/|title=Providing Public Transportation Alternatives for the Greater Phoenix Metro Area &#124; Valley Metro &#124;<!-- Bot generated title -->|archivedate=May 18, 2011}}</ref>  reprising a role played by the [[Phoenix Street Railway]] between 1911 and 1926.\n\n===Historic buildings===\nThere are numerous properties in the city of Glendale which are considered to be historical and have been included either in the [[National Register of Historic Places]]<ref name=\"nationalregisterofhistoricplaces.com\">{{cite web|url=https://nationalregisterofhistoricplaces.com/az/Maricopa/state.html|title=National Register of Historical Places - ARIZONA (AZ), Maricopa County|website=nationalregisterofhistoricplaces.com}}</ref> or the listings of the Glendale Arizona Historical Society. At the end of the article are some of these properties with a short description of the same.\n{{Further|List of historic properties in Glendale, Arizona}}\n\n{{Gallery\n|title=Historical Glendale, Arizona<br />(NRHP = National Register of Historic Places)<ref name=\"nationalregisterofhistoricplaces.com\"/><br />(GAHS=Glendale Arizona Historical Society-listed)\n|width=200\n|height=100\n|lines=4\n|align=center\n|File:G-Sugar Beet.jpg|'''Beet Sugar Factory Building''', built in 1906 (NRHP)\n|File:G-Manistee Ranch Mansion.jpg|Main mansion of the '''Manistee Ranch''', built in 1897 (NRHP)\n|File:Glendale-Sahuaro_Ranch_Main_Mansion_1X.jpg|Main mansion in '''Sahuaro Ranch''', built in 1886 (NRHP)\n|File:G-First National Bank of Glendale 1906.jpg|'''First National Bank of Glendale''', built in 1906 (NRHP)\n|File:G-EC_Bunch_House_1898.jpg|'''E.C. Bunch House''', built in 1898 (NRHP)\n|File:G-George_O'Dowdy_Cottage_1926.jpg|'''George O'Dowdy Rental Cottage''', built in 1926 (NRHP)\n|File:G-Glendale_Womens_Club_1912.jpg|'''Glendale Woman's Club''', structure built in 1912 (NRHP)\n|File:G-Jonas_McNair_House_1897.jpg|'''Jonas McNair House''', built in 1897 (NRHP)\n|File:G-C.H._Tinker_House-1913.jpg|'''C.H. Tinker House''', built 1913 (NRHP)\n|File:G-Glendale_Grammar_School One-room_Class_Building.jpg|'''Glendale Grammar School One-Room Class Building''', built in 1920 (NRHP)\n|File:G-Glendale High School Auditorium-1939.jpg|'''Glendale High School Auditorium''', built 1939 (NRHP)\n|File:G-Glendale Santa Fe Railroad Depot-1895.jpg|'''Santa Fe Railroad Depot''', built in 1895. The building serves as the offices of BNSF-MOW (Burlington Northern Santa Fe \u2013 Maintenance of Way) '''(GAHS)'''\n|File:Glendale-Murphy Park.JPG|'''Murphy Park'''.  The turn of the century town clock (pictured) was dedicated in 1987 to the memory of Thelma Renick Heatwole (1912\u20131991), who covered life in the Glendale community for more than 40 years as a newspaper reporter. The park is located at 58th & Glendale Avenues and has a public library.\n|File: Glendale-Forney_House-1893.JPG|The '''Forney House''', built in 1893, is the second oldest house in Glendale, Arizona. It is located at 7534 North 61st Avenue. The oldest house in Glendale is the Adobe house located in [[Saguaro Ranch]].\n|File: Phoenix-William_J._Murphy_House-1895.jpg|The historic '''[[William John Murphy|William John Murphy House]]''' was built in 1895 and is located at 7514 N. Central Ave. in Phoenix, Arizona. Even though the house is not located in Glendale, it served as the residence of William J. Murphy who created the Arizona Improvement Company in 1887 and bought land in areas that would eventually become the towns of [[Peoria, Arizona|Peoria]] and Glendale. The house is listed as historic by the [[Phoenix Historic Property Register]].\n}}\n\n====Catlin Court Historic District====\n{{Further|Catlin Court Historic District}}\n\n====Thunderbird 1 Army Air Field====\n{{Gallery\n|title=[[Thunderbird Field No. 1|Thunderbird 1 Army Air Field]]\n|width=200\n|height=100\n|lines=4\n|align=left\n|File:Glendale-Thunderbird_1_Army_Air_Field_Control_Tower-1941.jpg|The historic '''Thunderbird Control Tower''' was built in 1941 and served as the Air Control Tower and Officers' quarters during the operation of the Thunderbird 1 Army Air Field, in Glendale. There American, British, Canadian and Chinese pilots trained during WWII. The air field was deactivated in 1945 and is now occupied by the Thunderbird School of Global Management which is located southeast of the intersection of West Greenway Road & North 59th Avenue in Glendale, Arizona '''(GAHS)'''.\n|File: Glendale-Thunderbird_1_Army_Air_Field_Control_Tower-1941-2.jpg|Different view of the historic '''Thunderbird Control Tower'''. The tower and officer quarters were built in 1941 and served the Thunderbird 1 Army Air Field, in Glendale during WW II '''(GAHS)'''.\n|File: Glendale-Thunderbird 1 Army Air Field Hangar-1941.jpg|The historic '''Thunderbird 1 Army Air Field Airplane Hangar''' was built in 1941 '''(GAHS)'''.\n}}\n{{clear}}\n\n==Sister cities==\nGlendale has one sister city:\n*{{flagdeco|Norway}} \u2013 [[\u00d8rland]], Norway<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sister-cities.org/interactive-map/Glendale,%20Arizona|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170813190531/http://www.sister-cities.org/interactive-map/Glendale,%20Arizona|archivedate=2017-08-13|title=Interactive City Directory: Glendale, Arizona|publisher=sister-cities.org}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Geography|North America|United States|Arizona}}\n*[[List of historic properties in Glendale, Arizona]]\n*[[Adobe Mountain Desert Park]]\n*[[William John Murphy]] \u2013 Founder of Glendale\n*[[Catlin Court Historic District]]\n*[[USS Arizona salvaged artifacts]]\n*[[List of people from the Phoenix metropolitan area]]\n*[[Glendale Memorial Park Cemetery]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sister project links|voy=Glendale (Arizona)}}\n*[http://www.glendaleaz.com/ Official City Website]\n\n{{Geographic Location (8-way)\n | Northwest = [[Peoria, Arizona|Peoria]]\n | North = [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]], [[Peoria, Arizona|Peoria]], [[El Mirage, Arizona|El Mirage]], and  [[Surprise, Arizona|Surprise]]\n | Northeast = [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]]\n | West = [[Litchfield Park, Arizona|Litchfield Park]] and [[Buckeye, Arizona|Buckeye]]\n | Centre = ''Glendale''\n | East = [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]]\n | Southwest = [[Buckeye, Arizona|Buckeye]] and [[Goodyear, Arizona|Goodyear]]\n | South = [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]] and [[Avondale, Arizona|Avondale]]\n | Southeast = [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]]\n}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Articles relating to Glendale and [[Maricopa County, Arizona|Maricopa County]]\n| list =\n{{Maricopa County, Arizona}}\n\n{{Phoenix Metropolitan Area}}\n{{Arizona}}\n{{USLargestMetros}}\n{{Arizona cities and mayors of 100,000 population}}\n}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cities in Arizona]]\n[[Category:Glendale, Arizona| ]]\n[[Category:Cities in Maricopa County, Arizona]]\n[[Category:Phoenix metropolitan area]]\n[[Category:Populated places in the Sonoran Desert]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|City in Arizona, United States}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = Glendale\n|settlement_type          = [[City]]\n|image_skyline            = Glendale-Downtown Glendale.jpg\n|imagesize                = 260px\n|image_caption            = Downtown Glendale, Arizona as viewed from the intersections of Glendale Ave. and 58th Ave.\n|image_seal               = glendalelogo.jpg\n|image_map                = File:Maricopa County Arizona Incorporated and Unincorporated areas Glendale Highlighted 0427820.svg\n|mapsize                  = \n|map_caption              = Location of Glendale in Maricopa County, Arizona\n|image_map1               = \n|mapsize1                 = \n|map_caption1             = \n|pushpin_map              = USA\n|pushpin_map_caption      = Location in the United States\n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in Arizona|County]]\n|subdivision_name         = [[United States]]\n|subdivision_name1        = [[Arizona]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Maricopa County, Arizona|Maricopa]]\n|population_demonym       = Glendalian\n|government_type          = \n|leader_title             = [[Mayor]]\n|leader_name              = Jerry Weiers (Non-Partisan)\n|established_date         = \n|area_magnitude           = \n|area_total_km2           = 160.49\n|area_total_sq_mi         = 61.96\n|area_land_km2            = 159.45\n|area_land_sq_mi          = 61.56\n|area_water_km2           = 1.04\n|area_water_sq_mi         = 0.40\n|elevation_footnotes      = <ref name=gnis>{{Cite GNIS|5060|Glendale}}</ref>\n|elevation_ft             = 1152\n|elevation_m              = \n|population_as_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_est           = 250702\n|pop_est_as_of            = 2018\n|pop_est_footnotes        = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\"/>\n|population_footnotes     = <ref name =\"FactFinder\">{{cite web|title=American FactFinder|url=http://factfinder2.census.gov/faces/nav/jsf/pages/index.xhtml|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=June 18, 2012}}</ref>\n|population_total         = 226721\n|population_rank          = US: [[List of United States cities by population|89th]]\n|population_metro         = \n|population_density_km2   = 1572.28\n|population_density_sq_mi = 4072.15\n|timezone                 = [[Mountain Time Zone|MST]] (no [[Daylight savings time|DST]])\n|utc_offset               = -7\n|coordinates              = {{coord|33|32|19|N|112|11|11|W|region:US-AZ_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code_type         = ZIP code\n|postal_code              = 85301-85318\n|area_code                = [[Area code 623|623]] and [[Area code 602|602]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 04-27820\n|blank1_name              = GNIS_id = 5060<ref name=gnis/>\n|blank1_info              = \n|website                  = {{URL|www.glendaleaz.com}}\n|footnotes                = \n|unit_pref = Imperial\n|area_footnotes = <ref name=\"CenPopGazetteer2016\">{{cite web|title=2018 U.S. Gazetteer Files|url=https://www2.census.gov/geo/docs/maps-data/data/gazetteer/2018_Gazetteer/2018_gaz_place_04.txt|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=Jul 1, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Glendale''' {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u0261|l|\u025b|n|d|e\u026a|l}} is a city in [[Maricopa County, Arizona|Maricopa County]], [[Arizona]], [[United States]], located about nine miles (14&nbsp;km) northwest from [[Downtown Phoenix]]. According to the 2018 U.S. Census estimates, the population of the city is 250,702.<ref name =\"USCensusEst2018\"/>\n\n==History==\n{{Main|William John Murphy}}\nIn the late 1800s what is now known as Glendale, Arizona, was all desert. [[William John Murphy]], a native of [[New Hartford, New York]], who resided in the town of [[Flagstaff, Arizona|Flagstaff]] in what was then known as the territory of Arizona, was in charge of building a {{convert|40|mi|km|adj=mid|-long}} [[Arizona Canal]] from Granite Reef to New River for the Arizona Canal Company. In 1885, he completed the canal, which would bring water to the desert land.<ref name=\"M\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hmdb.org/marker.asp?marker=30433|title=William J. Murphy Historical Marker|website=www.hmdb.org}}</ref> Murphy was deep in debt, since he had agreed to be paid in Arizona Canal Company stock and bonds and land instead of cash.<ref name=\"SLRP\">{{cite web|url=http://www.waterhistory.org/histories/reclamation/saltriver/|title=WaterHistory.org|website=www.waterhistory.org}}</ref>\n[[File:William John Murphy.jpg|thumb|left|upright|William John Murphy \u2013 Founder of Glendale]]\nIn 1887, Murphy formed the Arizona Improvement Company. His objective was to sell the land and water rights south of the canal. Murphy had to raise capital from out of state sources in order to meet payroll and construction expenses.<ref name=\"SLRP\"/> Murphy decided to refer to this land as \"Glendale\". In order to develop and interest potential investors and settlers in this new town, Murphy decided to provide a better way of access from [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]] to Glendale and ending in the town of [[Peoria, Arizona|Peoria]] by building an {{convert|18|mi|km|adj=mid|-long}} diagonal road which he named Grand Avenue.\n\nIn 1891, Burgess Hadsell worked with Murphy to bring 70 Brethren and River Brethren families to Glendale to form a temperance colony. Soon settlers, attracted by the town's ban on alcoholic beverages, continued to arrive. In 1895, Murphy platted the original town site and amended the plat to include a town park and some business lots.  It was bounded by Lamar Road on the south, 55th Avenue on the east, Myrtle Avenue on the north, and 59th Avenue on the west.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.glendaleaz.com/economicdevelopment/documents/CCMP.pdf|title=Glendale City Center Master Plan|publisher=glendaleaz.com}}</ref> The construction of a railroad from Prescott to Phoenix was made possible with an exchange of the right-of-way made by Murphy along Grand Avenue.<ref name=\"M\"/>  The railroad allowed Glendale settlers to transport goods to the north and easily receive building materials.\n\nThe construction and commercial applications of the Beet Sugar Factory in 1906, also contributed to the growth of Glendale. Though the operations of the factory only lasted until 1913, it played an important role in the increase of immigrant and migrant settlers in the city.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://molokane.org/molokan/Locations/Americas/Arizona/Noon.htm|title=Beet Sugar Factory History, Glendale, Arizona|website=molokane.org}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nGlendale is located at {{Coord|33|32|19|N|112|11|11|W|type:city}} (33.538654, \u2212112.186261).<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/gazette.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=April 23, 2011|date=February 12, 2011|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref>\n\n===Climate===\n{{Phoenix weatherbox}}\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of {{convert|55.8|sqmi|km2}}, of which, {{convert|55.7|sqmi|km2}} of it is land and {{convert|0.1|sqmi|km2}} of it (0.13%) is water.\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1910= 1000\n|1920= 2737\n|1930= 3665\n|1940= 4855\n|1950= 8179\n|1960= 15893\n|1970= 36228\n|1980= 97172\n|1990= 147864\n|2000= 218812\n|2010= 226721\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=250702\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=June 4, 2019}}</ref>\n|align-fn=center\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref name=\"DecennialCensus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 4, 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n\nAs of the [[census]] of 2010, there were 226,710 people, 79,114 households, and 54,721 families residing in the city. The [[population density]] was 3,929.5 people per square mile (1,517.3/km\u00b2). There were 79,667 housing units at an average density of 1,430.7 per square mile (552.4/km\u00b2). The racial makeup of the city was 75.54% [[Race (United States Census)|White]], 6% [[Race (United States Census)|Black]] or [[Race (United States Census)|African American]], 1.7% [[Race (United States Census)|Native American]], 3.9% [[Race (United States Census)|Asian]], 0.2% [[Race (United States Census)|Pacific Islander]], 16.95% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 4.0% from two or more races. 35.5% of the population were [[Race (United States Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Race (United States Census)|Latino]] of any race.\n\nThere were 79,114 households out of which 39.9% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 53.5% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 12.8% had a female householder with no husband present, and 28.2% were non-families. 21.3% of all households were made up of individuals and 5.8% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.85 and the average family size was 3.33.\n\nIn the city, the population was spread out with 30.1% under the age of 18, 10.8% from 18 to 24, 31.9% from 25 to 44, 19.9% from 45 to 64, and 7.4% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 31 years. For every 100 females, there were 99.6 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 97.1 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the city was $45,015, and the median income for a family was $51,162. Males had a median income of $35,901 versus $27,736 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the city was $19,124. About 8.8% of families and 11.9% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 15.3% of those under age 18 and 9.5% of those age 65 or over.\n{{clear}}\n\n==Notable attractions==\n[[File:Glendale Glitters by Gage Skidmore.jpg|thumb|Downtown Glendale with Glendale Glitters around Christmas]]\n[[File:WestgateAtNight.jpg|thumb|The fountain area of the Westgate Entertainment District.]]\n\n* [[Adobe Mountain Desert Park]]\n* Glendale Chocolate Festival (every February)<ref name=\"glendaleaz.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.glendaleaz.com/events/|title=Glendale, AZ - Events and Festivals|website=www.glendaleaz.com}}</ref>  \n* Glendale Folk & Heritage Festival<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.azcentral.com/thingstodo/events/articles/20130320glendale-folk-heritage-festival-event.html|title=3/23-24: Glendale Folk & Heritage Festival|first=Kellie|last=Hwang|website=azcentral.com}}</ref> \n* Glendale Glitters (every December)<ref name=\"glendaleaz.com\"/>\n* Glendale Jazz and Blues Festival<ref name=\"glendaleaz.com\"/>\n* Historic [[Manistee Ranch]]\n* Historic [[Sahuaro Ranch]]\n* Cerreta Candy Co. factory tour<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tripsavvy.com/cerreta-candy-company-factory-tour-2681124|title=The Sweetest Tour in Glendale, Arizona|website=TripSavvy}}</ref>\n* Downtown Glendale featuring antique shops and restaurants\n* [[Deer Valley Rock Art Center]]\n*[[State Farm Stadium]]\n*[[Gila River Arena]]\n*Brelby Theatre Company\n*Spotlight Youth Theatre\n* [[Elsie McCarthy Sensory Garden]]\n* Westgate Entertainment District\n\n==Sports==\n[[File:Westgateground.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Westgate City Center]][[File:Cardinals stadium crop.jpg|thumb|right|[[State Farm Stadium]]]]\n[[File:Glendale-arena.jpg|thumb|left|[[Gila River Arena]]]]\n[[File:University of Phoenix Stadium (Glendale).jpg|thumb|right|Ground level of the stadium.]]\n\nGlendale is the site of two major sports venues:  [[State Farm Stadium]] and [[Gila River Arena]]. Both venues are part of the Glendale Sports and Entertainment District development plan, meant to spur growth in the sparsely inhabited Yucca district. Both venues are owned by the City of Glendale.\n\nState Farm Stadium has been the home field of the [[Arizona Cardinals]] in the [[National Football League]] since 2006, and the annual [[Fiesta Bowl]] college football game since 2007. Both the Cardinals and bowl game moved from [[Sun Devil Stadium]] on the [[Arizona State University]] campus in [[Tempe, Arizona|Tempe]]. Since opening, the facility has brought two [[Super Bowl]]s, three college football national championship games, the [[NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|NCAA Men's Basketball Final Four]], [[WrestleMania XXVI]] and [[International Champions Cup]] soccer to Glendale. Designed by architect Peter Eisenman, the stadium was featured on [[History (U.S. TV channel)|The History Channel]] TV series, ''[[Modern Marvels]]'' because of its roll-out natural grass field.\n\n[[Gila River Arena]] (formerly Glendale Arena, then Jobing.com Arena) and [[Westgate City Center]] is adjacent to State Farm Stadium, and is the home of the [[Arizona Coyotes]] of the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL). It was also the home of the now defunct [[Arizona Sting]] of the [[National Lacrosse League]] (NLL). The inaugural [[Street League Skateboarding]] event was held in the summer of 2010 in Glendale at the Gila River Arena. This street skateboarding competition returns to Glendale annually.\n\nIn 2009, the [[Los Angeles Dodgers]] and the [[Chicago White Sox]]  of [[Major League Baseball]] began to share the new  [[Camelback Ranch|Camelback Ranch-Glendale]] spring training complex and stadium in Glendale owned and operated by the City of Glendale.\n\n==Education==\n[[File:Glendale-1917 Nash Fire Truck.jpg|thumb|right|This 1917 Nash Fire Truck was the first motorized fire truck of the Glendale Fire Department. The truck was manufactured by the [[Nash Motors|Nash Motors Company]] and is on exhibit at the Glendale Training Center located at 11330 W. Glendale Ave. in Glendale, Arizona.]]\nThere are a number of higher education campuses in Glendale. [[Glendale Community College (Arizona)|Glendale Community College]] and Glendale Community College North, just across the border in northwestern Phoenix, are members of the [[Maricopa County Community College District]]. [[Arizona State University's]] [[Thunderbird School of Global Management]] was founded in Glendale at Thunderbird Field after World War II and recently relocated its campus to the downtown location of ASU after joining the university as an independent unit dedicated to international business education. [[Arizona State University at the West campus|West]] campus is just across the border from Glendale in west Phoenix.  [[Midwestern University]] is a graduate college of medicine located in Glendale.\n\nMany [[school districts]] serve the city of Glendale.\n\nThe following school districts serve the city:\n*Unified school districts\n**[[Deer Valley Unified School District]]\n**[[Dysart Unified School District]]\n**[[Peoria Unified School District]] (headquartered in Glendale)<ref>\"[https://www.peoriaud.k12.az.us/Pages/DistrictOverview.aspx District Overview]\" {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120730183918/https://www.peoriaud.k12.az.us/Pages/DistrictOverview.aspx |date=July 30, 2012 }}</ref>\n*High school districts\n**[[Glendale Union High School District]]\n**[[Phoenix Union High School District]]\n**Tolleson Union High School District\n*Elementary school districts\n**[[Alhambra Elementary School District]]\n**Glendale Elementary School District\n**Pendergast Elementary School District\n**[[Washington Elementary School District]]\n\nGrace Lutheran School is a Pre-K-8 Christian school of the [[Wisconsin Evangelical Lutheran Synod]] (WELS) in Glendale.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.graceglendale.org/school/|title=School|website=Grace Evangelical Lutheran Church}}</ref>\n\n==Transportation==\nThe city of Glendale has a roughly average percentage of households without a car. In 2015, 8.4 percent of Glendale households lacked a car, and increased slightly to 9 percent in 2016. The national average was 8.7 percent in 2016. Glendale averaged 1.72 cars per household in 2016, compared to a national average of 1.8.<ref>{{cite web|title=Car Ownership in U.S. Cities Data and Map|journal=Governing|url=http://www.governing.com/gov-data/car-ownership-numbers-of-vehicles-by-city-map.html|accessdate=May 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Martha McSally and Jerry Weiers.jpg|thumb|Glendale Mayor Jerry Weiers with Martha McSally in 2020.]]\n==Notable people==\n<!-- NOTICE * * * NOTICE * * * NOTICE * * * * * * * * * * * *NOTICE * * * NOTICE * * * NOTICE\u2022 Only people who already have a Wikipedia article may appear here. This establishes notability.\n\u2022 The article must mention how they are associated with the community, whether born, raised, or residing.\n\u2022 The fact of their association should have a reliable source cited, or it should be stated in their Wikipedia article\n\u2022 Alphabetical by last name please\n\u2022 All others will be deleted without further explanation\nEND OF NOTICE * * * * * * * * * * * * END OF NOTICE * * * * * * * * * * * *END OF NOTICE -->\n*[[Prince Amukamara]] \u2013 professional football player\n*[[Eddie Bonine]] \u2013 professional baseball player\n*[[Elijah Burke]] \u2013 professional wrestler\n*[[Daniel Cruz (soccer)|Danny Cruz]] \u2013 professional soccer player\n*[[Nick Evans (baseball)|Nick Evans]] \u2013 professional baseball player\n*[[Trent Franks]] \u2013  former United States congressman\n*[[Lauren Froderman]] \u2013 winner of ''So You Think You Can Dance'' (Season 7)\n*[[Jennie Garth]] \u2013 actress\n*[[Benson Henderson]] \u2013 former UFC Lightweight Champion<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ufc.com/fighter/Benson-Henderson | publisher=UFC | title=Benson Henderson | accessdate=September 5, 2014 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140819071228/http://www.ufc.com/fighter/Benson-Henderson | archivedate=August 19, 2014}}</ref>\n*[[Job for a Cowboy]] \u2013 death metal band formed in Glendale in 2003\n*[[Paul LoDuca]] \u2013 professional baseball player\n*[[Craig Mabbitt]] \u2013 lead vocalist of band [[Escape The Fate]]\n*[[Michael McDowell (racing driver)|Michael McDowell]] \u2013 NASCAR driver\n*[[Evan Mecham]] \u2013 Arizona governor\n*[[Lou Novikoff]] \u2013 professional baseball player\n*[[Sterling Ridge]] \u2013 Arizona legislator\n*[[Marty Robbins]] \u2013 Grammy-winning country musician and auto racer\n*[[Nate Ruess]] \u2013 lead singer of [[Fun (band)|Fun]]\n*[[Tage Thompson]] - NHL player for the [[Buffalo Sabres]]\n*[[Jason Zumwalt]] \u2013 actor\n\n==Culture==\n===Arizona's Antique Capital===\nGlendale bills itself as \"Arizona's Antique Capital\", with support for its claim from both ''[[Sunset (magazine)|Sunset]]'' magazine ([https://web.archive.org/web/20081031092720/http://www.sunset.com/sunset/travel/article/0%2C20633%2C710517%2C00.html 2004]) and a 1998 article in ''[[USA Today]]''. Glendale is home to the popular [[Arrowhead Towne Center]] mall in the northwest part of the city. Glendale also is home to [[Midwestern University]], metropolitan Phoenix's first medical school, as well as a major post-graduate international business school: the [[Thunderbird School of Global Management]].\n\nAn extension of [[Valley Metro Rail]] service is planned to serve the city, opening in 2026,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.valleymetro.org/metro_light_rail/future_extensions/glendale/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110518122555/http://www.valleymetro.org/metro_light_rail/future_extensions/glendale/|title=Providing Public Transportation Alternatives for the Greater Phoenix Metro Area &#124; Valley Metro &#124;<!-- Bot generated title -->|archivedate=May 18, 2011}}</ref>  reprising a role played by the [[Phoenix Street Railway]] between 1911 and 1926.\n\n===Historic buildings===\nThere are numerous properties in the city of Glendale which are considered to be historical and have been included either in the [[National Register of Historic Places]]<ref name=\"nationalregisterofhistoricplaces.com\">{{cite web|url=https://nationalregisterofhistoricplaces.com/az/Maricopa/state.html|title=National Register of Historical Places - ARIZONA (AZ), Maricopa County|website=nationalregisterofhistoricplaces.com}}</ref> or the listings of the Glendale Arizona Historical Society. At the end of the article are some of these properties with a short description of the same.\n{{Further|List of historic properties in Glendale, Arizona}}\n\n{{Gallery\n|title=Historical Glendale, Arizona<br />(NRHP = National Register of Historic Places)<ref name=\"nationalregisterofhistoricplaces.com\"/><br />(GAHS=Glendale Arizona Historical Society-listed)\n|width=200\n|height=100\n|lines=4\n|align=center\n|File:G-Sugar Beet.jpg|'''Beet Sugar Factory Building''', built in 1906 (NRHP)\n|File:G-Manistee Ranch Mansion.jpg|Main mansion of the '''Manistee Ranch''', built in 1897 (NRHP)\n|File:Glendale-Sahuaro_Ranch_Main_Mansion_1X.jpg|Main mansion in '''Sahuaro Ranch''', built in 1886 (NRHP)\n|File:G-First National Bank of Glendale 1906.jpg|'''First National Bank of Glendale''', built in 1906 (NRHP)\n|File:G-EC_Bunch_House_1898.jpg|'''E.C. Bunch House''', built in 1898 (NRHP)\n|File:G-George_O'Dowdy_Cottage_1926.jpg|'''George O'Dowdy Rental Cottage''', built in 1926 (NRHP)\n|File:G-Glendale_Womens_Club_1912.jpg|'''Glendale Woman's Club''', structure built in 1912 (NRHP)\n|File:G-Jonas_McNair_House_1897.jpg|'''Jonas McNair House''', built in 1897 (NRHP)\n|File:G-C.H._Tinker_House-1913.jpg|'''C.H. Tinker House''', built 1913 (NRHP)\n|File:G-Glendale_Grammar_School One-room_Class_Building.jpg|'''Glendale Grammar School One-Room Class Building''', built in 1920 (NRHP)\n|File:G-Glendale High School Auditorium-1939.jpg|'''Glendale High School Auditorium''', built 1939 (NRHP)\n|File:G-Glendale Santa Fe Railroad Depot-1895.jpg|'''Santa Fe Railroad Depot''', built in 1895. The building serves as the offices of BNSF-MOW (Burlington Northern Santa Fe \u2013 Maintenance of Way) '''(GAHS)'''\n|File:Glendale-Murphy Park.JPG|'''Murphy Park'''.  The turn of the century town clock (pictured) was dedicated in 1987 to the memory of Thelma Renick Heatwole (1912\u20131991), who covered life in the Glendale community for more than 40 years as a newspaper reporter. The park is located at 58th & Glendale Avenues and has a public library.\n|File: Glendale-Forney_House-1893.JPG|The '''Forney House''', built in 1893, is the second oldest house in Glendale, Arizona. It is located at 7534 North 61st Avenue. The oldest house in Glendale is the Adobe house located in [[Saguaro Ranch]].\n|File: Phoenix-William_J._Murphy_House-1895.jpg|The historic '''[[William John Murphy|William John Murphy House]]''' was built in 1895 and is located at 7514 N. Central Ave. in Phoenix, Arizona. Even though the house is not located in Glendale, it served as the residence of William J. Murphy who created the Arizona Improvement Company in 1887 and bought land in areas that would eventually become the towns of [[Peoria, Arizona|Peoria]] and Glendale. The house is listed as historic by the [[Phoenix Historic Property Register]].\n}}\n\n====Catlin Court Historic District====\n{{Further|Catlin Court Historic District}}\n\n====Thunderbird 1 Army Air Field====\n{{Gallery\n|title=[[Thunderbird Field No. 1|Thunderbird 1 Army Air Field]]\n|width=200\n|height=100\n|lines=4\n|align=left\n|File:Glendale-Thunderbird_1_Army_Air_Field_Control_Tower-1941.jpg|The historic '''Thunderbird Control Tower''' was built in 1941 and served as the Air Control Tower and Officers' quarters during the operation of the Thunderbird 1 Army Air Field, in Glendale. There American, British, Canadian and Chinese pilots trained during WWII. The air field was deactivated in 1945 and is now occupied by the Thunderbird School of Global Management which is located southeast of the intersection of West Greenway Road & North 59th Avenue in Glendale, Arizona '''(GAHS)'''.\n|File: Glendale-Thunderbird_1_Army_Air_Field_Control_Tower-1941-2.jpg|Different view of the historic '''Thunderbird Control Tower'''. The tower and officer quarters were built in 1941 and served the Thunderbird 1 Army Air Field, in Glendale during WW II '''(GAHS)'''.\n|File: Glendale-Thunderbird 1 Army Air Field Hangar-1941.jpg|The historic '''Thunderbird 1 Army Air Field Airplane Hangar''' was built in 1941 '''(GAHS)'''.\n}}\n{{clear}}\n\n==Sister cities==\nGlendale has one sister city:\n*{{flagdeco|Norway}} \u2013 [[\u00d8rland]], Norway<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sister-cities.org/interactive-map/Glendale,%20Arizona|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170813190531/http://www.sister-cities.org/interactive-map/Glendale,%20Arizona|archivedate=2017-08-13|title=Interactive City Directory: Glendale, Arizona|publisher=sister-cities.org}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Geography|North America|United States|Arizona}}\n*[[List of historic properties in Glendale, Arizona]]\n*[[Adobe Mountain Desert Park]]\n*[[William John Murphy]] \u2013 Founder of Glendale\n*[[Catlin Court Historic District]]\n*[[USS Arizona salvaged artifacts]]\n*[[List of people from the Phoenix metropolitan area]]\n*[[Glendale Memorial Park Cemetery]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==